into a passive postion for black.} 12. O-O Rac8 13. Rac1 Rfd8 14. b3 a6 15. Nd4
Ne4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Rfd1 Kg7 18. Ne2 Qd6 19. f3 Bf5 20. e4 Bd7 21. Qe3 b5 22.
Bd3 Bb2 23. Rb1 Ba3 24. b4 {The black bishop can find itself sidelined here.
White has to act quickly before black brings it back into the game.} a5 25. e5
Qc7 {[%tqu "En","There are many tempting continuations here. Which do you
think is best?","","","d5d6","",10]} 26. d6 $1 exd6 27. exd6 Qb8 28. Nf4 Bxb4 {
[%tqu ]} 29. Nh5+ {The critical position. Young Anton finds the right idea but
in the wrong move order! The spectators were not sure themselves since at one
stage it looks winning and then one finds a defence then you break that down
